article.headline: Hot-shooting Parker finishes with 25 points, seven assists
article.linkText: Parker gets No. 21 Tulsa rolling past TCU
article.story: TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Tulsa guard Jason Parker said his team's struggling to put away Texas Christian shouldn't be a major concern. Parker had 25 points and seven assists Monday night as the Golden Hurricane (No. 21 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 Associated Press) beat the Horned Frogs 78-65 for its third consecutive victory. ''We come out playing great basketball and then we have letdowns,'' Parker said. ''That is synonymous at this time of the season with a lot of teams. It isn't something to worry about, but if we want to go to where we want to at the end of the season, we will have to play smash-mouth basketball to win the games.'' Parker was 8-for-14 from the field, including 4-for-7 from 3-point range. He also grabbed five rebounds and held TCU's Corey Santee under his scoring average with 12 points on 4-for-12 shooting. ''He's doing such a super job,'' Tulsa coach John Phillips said of Parker. ''Besides shooting the ball really well and the assists, he did a real good job on Santee. He's really coming through for us.'' The Golden Hurricane (7-1) scored the game's first 11 points and the Horned Frogs (4-5) never got closer than four the rest of the night. Tulsa led 69-63 when Parker hit a 3-pointer with 1:41 left and then added two free throws 20 seconds later to break the game open. ''We had a chance to steal this game down the stretch, but we just didn't make enough plays,'' TCU coach Neil Dougherty said. TCU was held to its lowest point total of the season in its third consecutive defeat although Dougherty called it his team's ''best effort for a complete basketball game.'' ''Our effort level was good enough to compete with a team the caliber of Tulsa,'' he said. ''It hasn't always been that way. Now we have to learn how to finish plays, possessions and games. We have to do all the little things in a close game like this.'' Dante Swanson added 15 points and seven rebounds for Tulsa, while Kevin Johnson and Jarius Glenn each had 11 points. Johnson had 10 rebounds. Jamal Brown paced TCU with 16 points and 12 rebounds, while Junior Blount had 14 points in his first collegiate game in his hometown, but was only 3-for-14 from the field. Parker had 16 points in the first half as Tulsa took a 38-27 lead. The Golden Hurricane boosted that margin to 50-36 with 17:02 left. Marqus Ledoux, who did not score in the first half, contributed seven points during that 12-9 spurt. But over the next six minutes, TCU outscored Tulsa 16-6 to reduce its deficit to 56-52. The Golden Hurricane countered with a 7-1 run. TCU would not go away, responding with six consecutive points to close to 63-59 with 6:55 remaining. Neither team scored again until Swanson hit a 3-pointer at 4:27. Swanson added a layup at 3:16, but Blount answered with a 3 and a free throw to cut it to 68-63 at 2:51. The Horned Frogs, however, could not get any closer. TCU shot 33 percent from the field and was just 19-for-32 from the free throw line. Tulsa shot 47 percent from the field and was 15-for-27 from the line. It was the first meeting for the teams, who were once Western Athletic Conference rivals, since TCU moved to Conference USA after the 2000-01 season.
